  dialogueLines:
  - 'Dear Nightingale, what troubles you? You sing a song that makes men long to
    die! '
  - "Have you come to state the obvious? Hoopoe, I hadn\u2019t taken you for such
    a foul-spirited mocking-bird! "
  - 'Wait a moment, I- '
  - 'My sweet rose is gone; from her dear presence I could never stir. Begone, I
    am in no mood for your platitudes. You may certainly now take your leave. '
  - 'If you truly wish for me to go, then I will. But I know something of lost love
    myself, and you need not be alone in sorrow. '
  - "What could you know of my pain? My grief is one that no bird knows\u2013 the
    only one who understood was my dear Rose. Without her, my continued existence
    is without reason. "
  - "You are only a child. If you live to grow old, may fate rip your life\u2019s
    purpose away from you as it has mine. Then you might begin to understand.  "
  - 'Until then, learn to keep your nose out of the business of your elders! '
  - "Your life\u2019s purpose? I could lend an ear at the very least\u2013 or perhaps;
    I could share with you a verse of my own? "
  - "Why, so that you may measure your sorrow against mine? \u2026Fine. Humor me
    with your sniveling. "
  - 'Do you not see? Rose is not gone, she is with you. She is in your heart and
    in this egg. It is only you who waits for the past. How can you continue on when
    you live for who you once were? '
  - 'You write with grace. But your words cannot beguile me. '
  - "As he turns away, Majnun notices a slight trembling in the bird\u2019s form.
    Without a word further, Nightingale takes off into the night sky."
  otherLines:
  - "Your intrusion is unwanted. My plumage is unmatched, yet they cast me out for
    Snake\u2019s lies. I am in no mood for your platitudes. Pester someone else! "
  - "You\u2026 speak as one who has tasted exile. But my paradise of perfection is
    lost forever to the snake. What use is your pity? "
  - "You followed\u2026 even with that cursed thing. Why? "
  - "Your words pierce deeper than any thorn. Isolation has only worsened this self-hatred.
    Leaning on another\u2026 it is not weakness?"
  - "Then I will return with you. This feather proves the snake\u2019s deception\u2014his
    lies that turned my pride to poison. I lashed out because I feared my own incompleteness.
    No more hiding. "
  - "You have shown me what the manuscripts whisper: outer splendor is illusion.
    The soul\u2019s pace is its own paradise. Thank you, wanderer. I am no longer
    banished from myself. "
  - "You have shown me what the manuscripts whisper: outer splendor is illusion.
    The soul\u2019s pace is its own paradise. Thank you, wanderer. I am no longer
    banished from myself. "
